        {
            "id": "action",
            "instance": "ff0c55a4-413b-47a7-96a4-36a46eecc038",
            "properties": [
                [
                    "name",
                    "Spearphishing Attachment"
                ],
                [
                    "ttp",
                    [
                        [
                            "tactic",
                            "TA0001"
                        ],
                        [
                            "technique",
                            "T1566.001"
                        ]
                    ]
                ],
                [
                    "description",
                    "MedusaLocker phishing emails carry malicious attachments — typically macro-enabled Microsoft Office documents (.docm, .xlsm) or password-protected archives containing executable payloads — that execute a dropper or loader upon opening. The attachment delivers the MedusaLocker ransomware binary or an intermediary loader that establishes a foothold on the victim host, disables security tooling, and begins the encryption routine after a configurable delay (typically 15–30 minutes post-execution) to allow the payload time to propagate across reachable network shares before detection. MedusaLocker's attachment-based delivery is the sole confirmed phishing sub-technique in reporting, reflecting the group's preference for direct payload delivery over credential harvesting via link-based lures."
                ],
                [
                    "confidence",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_start",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_end",
                    null
                ]
            ],
