        {
            "id": "action",
            "instance": "7c9910e9-ed7a-49e4-a4dc-5ee7bb022391",
            "properties": [
                [
                    "name",
                    "External Remote Services"
                ],
                [
                    "ttp",
                    [
                        [
                            "tactic",
                            "TA0001"
                        ],
                        [
                            "technique",
                            "T1133"
                        ]
                    ]
                ],
                [
                    "description",
                    "MedusaLocker affiliates leverage external remote access services — primarily Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) exposed to the internet — as both an initial access vector and a persistence mechanism (T1133 appears in both initial-access and persistence tactics, each with 1 report). Internet-facing RDP endpoints, common in the SME environments MedusaLocker targets, are accessed using credentials obtained via brute force, credential stuffing from prior breaches, or purchased from initial access brokers. RDP access provides the attacker with an interactive session on a network-connected host from which to disable Windows Defender and other security tools (T1562.001, T1562.009), execute the ransomware payload via PowerShell (T1059.001), and propagate the encryptor to network shares and remote hosts. The dual role of T1133 as both entry point and persistence mechanism reflects MedusaLocker's lean, RDP-centric operational style that requires minimal tooling beyond the ransomware binary itself."
                ],
                [
                    "confidence",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_start",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_end",
                    null
                ]
            ],
